"Thank you for your bravery" is the most common eulogy on flowers.

This article first appeared at southern weekend and is not to be reprinted without permission

By Li Zailei and Li Yang, southern weekend journalists

Editor in chief | Zhang Yue

(Li Yang / Video)

February 7 was the first day of the death of Dr Li Wenliang at Wuhan Central Hospital. The tributes continued all day at the gates of the hospital's outpatient building.

At about nine o'clock in the evening, mourners at the entrance of the hospital whistled, a shrill whistle cutting through the night. In the downtown area of Wuhan, many residents spontaneously organized a memorial service for Li Wenliang. People lit up the lights, blew whistles and shouted "Go Wuhan! "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(Lee jae-lei / Photo)

During the day on Feb. 7, the wife of Dr. Li Wenliang, who lives in her mother's home in Zaoyang, Hubei Province, posted an appeal for help. The southern weekend reporter contacted the phone number posted on the post to confirm that it was not her, but a relative, who could not be reached at this number.

Southern weekend journalists went to Zaoyang, but the only Xiangyang that had previously been described as open was closed to freeways and its Zaoyang, where the strictest closure orders were in place to allow strangers in and out. The southern weekend reporter had to turn back on a trail 30 kilometers from Zaoyang.

At 21pm, southern weekend reporters were in front of the clinic building of Wuhan Central Hospital and saw people still dropping off flowers. Outside the hospital, three black and white photographs of Li wearing a mask, his face surrounded by yellow and white chrysanthemums and dotted with lights.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
An older brother bowed, unable to contain his grief, and hid himself in a corner, holding the railing and sobbing. "Dr. Li Wenliang, thank you for your bravery, " he wrote on the flower's sticker

"Thank you for your bravery" is the most common eulogy on flowers. In addition, Wuhan residents told the doctor, who had just left, "good luck, hero, " "Li Wenliang, thank you for coming, " "citizen Li Wenliang, " and "Dr. Li Wenliang, thank you for everything you've done! "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(Lai Yeung / photo)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(Lee jae-lei / Video)

The owner of a nearby wood-tech Florist said they closed down soon after the city was closed. Just today, there are so many people calling to order flowers that they want to buy some flowers for Li Wenliang. He shuttled back and forth between the flower shop and the hospital.
